{"title": "Our Mages Are Different", "content": "How does someone become a mage? Why should someone have the power to alter reality? Obviously, mages use magic \u2014 but how does one gain access to magic? Look no further - this page will detail them.\n\nNote that these analogies could be mixed: for instance, it is possible that the innate ability to wield magic is based on bloodline (as with the mage race), but that to develop this innate ability, the mage must use ancient lore (as with the scholarly mage). Also note that this is about how the mage acquires power, not the source of that power: i.e., whether magic is drawn from nature, from the elements, from other planes, from the spirit world, or whatever.\n\nIt is also possible that there are multiple kinds of mages in one setting; sometimes they are mutually exclusive, sometimes they can be mixed (see above). When one of them is supposedly rare or unusual in universe, see Wrong Context Magic.\n\nDespite the name, this can sometimes apply to Differently Powered Individual as well; see also How to Give a Character Superpowers.\n\nOftentimes there'll be discussions about how one type of mage differs from another.\n\nSee also Functional Magic and Magic by Any Other Name for \"Our Magic Is Different\". If magic is something that not everyone can do, but mages still also need special education, that's Training the Gift of Magic. Compare Magicians Are Wizards (when stage magicians are lumped together with actual magic users).", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/OurMagesAreDifferent", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/TabletopGame/DungeonsAndDragons", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/FullmetalAlchemist", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/LightNovel/ACertainMagicalIndex", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/LyricalNanoha", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/PuellaMagiMadokaMagica", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/OjamajoDoremi", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/OnePiece", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/Naruto", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/FairyTail", "/pmw